Architects have understood that offices also need childcare
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the Arch.Design company.
No one would say that in its interior also hides a small nursery with everything of its own to such facilities: colorful walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, the children of Arch.Design employees have been able to visit it.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, from which many well-known buildings from Brno came out, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-guard.
The company employs about 90 people, mainly at the age of the baby boom and wanted to allow architects and designers to return to work soon after maternity.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, the nursery is one of the benefits that Arch.Design offers to its employees within the framework of its social program.
Constructors and architects thus have the opportunity to combine a demanding profession with the care of children.
The miniguard was an idea of Arch.Designu’s own employees and, with the support of the management, managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company’s mini-guarding is financed through the European Social Fund within the framework of the Operational Programme on Human Resources and Employment, as well as the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the funding granted (equipment of more than 2.8 million Czech crowns) they were able to purchase the equipment and, after two years, hire qualified personnel and services.
When the funding runs out (two years), the company Arch.Design has the obligation to keep the mini-guardia in operation with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and the company Economy Rating contributed to the submission of the funding application.
The care of children is in the hands of qualified staff; a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present throughout the day for their care. The kindergarten currently accommodates children with no age limit, although most of them are less than three years old.
Since it is a "miniguardia", it can only accommodate a maximum of five children simultaneously, although with shifts they come more during the day.
The operation of the nursery is flexible to adapt to the needs of the parents and children of all workers have the same right to use the nursery, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although it is an individual teaching and care, the contents of the mini-guardia program are comparable to the usual pre-school teaching program.
In it, children not only play, but also receive quality teaching: from basic learning to school preparation, they teach to English.
The class not only has toys and board games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go to see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up school children late when they are away from their workplace.
Parents are more productive while they work.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a loyalty relationship between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is among the firm companies that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program strengthened the marketing of staff.
The house of the bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. Watch Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s interiors
The roof resembles the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs resemble the column of a dinosaur, and the balconies resemble the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
Because of its shape similar to a skeleton, the locals dubbed it "the house of bones".
Its organic shapes, its striking colors, the novel use of stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade reminiscent of scales and the ubiquitous gently curved lines, all this is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
The cover of the house plays with dream lines, delicate colors and textures taken from nature and fauna.
Paying more attention, one observes a certain geometry, rhythm and a carefully thought out order.
At night, the entire facade of the house looks even more impressive, since it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors improves.
Snake and twisting of forms continues to surprise us also inside.
The corrugated wood copies the frames of the windows, the railings, the ornaments of the doors, the mirrors and the signs.
Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, located in the Eixample district at number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Gr<0xC3><0xA1>cia, emerged from the remodeling of an 1877 house by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction took two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the industrial rich Josep Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, initially insisted on demolishing the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s idea of a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, consisting of several apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> alone.
The architect Josep Mar<0xC3><0xAD>a Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in their plans of the project came up ornaments for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the mosaics used on the facade.
On the facade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> was the beginning of Jujol’s successful collaboration with Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
Jujol participated in the construction of Casa Mil<0xC3><0xA1> and Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s Güell Park, where other pieces of it are located.
Due to its organic form, the locals soon after its completion dubbed it "the house of bones".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows began to call it "the house of the squirrels".
It is also said that, at the top of the construction, appears the sword of San Jorge, patron of Catalonia.
Other sculptural elements of construction hide religious motifs.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> designed in the house a unique system for the central heating season with ventilation fans and typical fireplaces.
Its forty-five-degree inclination may be strange.
During construction, Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> did not respect the building standards of the moment at all and was not influenced by them.
Even so, the construction obtained the corresponding permission from the beginning, although obviously in it the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years after its completion, the town hall was so impressed with the result that it asked to be corrected.
It bothered him, for example, that the construction included columns even to the public sidewalk.
The arrangements were never made, rather the opposite: just fifteen days after the request of the city council, Josep Batll<0xC3><0xB3> requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two tallest floors of the building.
On the lower floors the owner himself was installed.
In the gallery on the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The six-storey house is completely crossed by a staircase leading to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all the angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> also worked with the modern concept of connecting space.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the lounges and a larger group can communicate in this way without renouncing the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with the reconstruction of Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>, not only obtained a new fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> plays with the light, white and blue tiles that cover the interior patio and candles.
The game with the two colors brings the maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was based simply on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which, on the contrary, absorb the sun's rays.
Anyone can visit Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and recharged apartment of those accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that this is a very beneficial business and expanded the visits to the common area and the dam, including the roof terrace.
The price of entry to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, pensioners and holders of tourist cards get a 20% discount.
The amount significantly exceeds the price of the entrance of other buildings of Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> in the city.
