According to Pilin of Macro Weil, for that reason, tests are currently being carried out with devices that look like a digital clock.
“In addition, they will have the added advantage that a potential aggressor may not identify the device.”
“Or that identifies him after a certain amount of time, which can make the police save time,” he adds.
Although the tracking devices are carried on the wrist or hanging, they will continue to use the same technology that is used for vehicle tracking.
This is the check of the position with a GPS system (which is used in the usual navigation in the car) combined with the function of a mobile phone that communicates the current position.
The army has enough mechanics to surround the whole Czech Republic. But it only lasts two years
The Czech army bought 445 kilometers of mecha to arrest explosives.
Last year, the Ministry of Defense added 224 kilometers of mecha to its arsenal.
Therefore, they have stocks for 225 years.
The problem is that the lifespan of the mecha is two years, four at most.
The army bought the explosives mecha from the STV Group, a.s. for forty million kroner.
The General’s staff responded to MF DNES justifying the purchase of such a huge amount of mecha by saying that soldiers need for training maneuvers 60 kilometers of mecha per year.
According to the calculations of the pyrotechnics of the army, with whom MF DNES was contacted, it is nevertheless decided that, in such a case, such maneuvers should be carried out with frequent use of explosives each year also all generals, high-ranking officers, and even secretaries and cleaners.
They did not want to be exempt either from the Minister of Defense Alexandr Vondr and the captain of the army Vlastimil Picek.
Only in this way could it be justified for the army to spend sixty kilometers of mecha.
This is equivalent to 25,000 explosions.
Even if it were, the army would have enough stocks for more than ten years.
On the contrary, as experts say, for the initial training of each new professional arrives with a maximum of two meters of mecha, the army would have with the new purchase (even adding the consumption of the engineer or special units) sufficient stocks for the 225 mentioned above.
The soldiers of the rapid intervention brigade complained personally recently to Minister Vondra because they say they barely have ammunition for various weapons, so even the practice of firing for money is limited.
And let’s not talk about the lack of underwear.
"I also fail to understand that we repeatedly buy such amounts of mecha."
“But it’s their decision, and they’ll know why they act that way.”
