Defense Ministry spokesman Jan Pej<0xC5><0xA1>ek defended the hundreds of miles of mecha by also saying that he will have stockpiles of this "munition" for at least ten years.
However, Jan D<0xC4><0x9B>ck<0xC3><0xBD>, of STV Group, indicates that the mecha only has a shelf life of four years and, in the case of pyrotechnic products for the army or the police, two years.
“If stored in perfect conditions, it can last up to four,” says one of the soldiers who, due to possible criticism from the army, does not want to give his name.
After the end of its useful life, each ammunition must be carefully checked to see if it remains reliable and will not harm the soldiers.
But these tests are not free and require an additional investment.
Another argument of the Ministry is that, by buying 445 kilometers of mecha, he got a discount.
