"When they manage to grab a bottle of your father's milkshake, it can be whiskey, but it's usually Fernet and vodka."
“Vodka has the advantage of being smooth with juice and not smelling as much,” he explains.
This is confirmed by Motol University Hospital spokeswoman Eva Jurinov<0xC3><0xA1>.
"Normally, it's either Fernet or rum."
“These are modern alcoholic beverages, particularly among schoolchildren.”
“In some cases, they use shaving cream that they picked up at home,” Jurinov<0xC3><0xA1> adds.
According to Pelik<0xC3><0xA1>n, they are drinkers of thirteen and fourteen years old who usually appear in hospitals.
Before Ho<0xC5><0x99>ovice, where he has worked since this year, he worked for a decade in pediatrics in Motol, where ambulances took young people from nearby areas.
"A girl had to come in maybe four times."
