A more moderate side of order maintenance is promoted in China
As an urban instructor sergeant, Tang Shenbin marked the passage in a town square, severely inspecting the nervous people in his charge, issuing low-pitched orders with military authority.
He wanted the female members of Chengguan, the corpulent police of China’s urban order, feared and despised for their capricious energetic measures and inclination to violence, to convey a certain impression to a handful of spectators.
"Firms!"
"Attention!"
Show them, he whispered, "how beautiful the girls are!"
Four girls who barely passed adolescence with identical white gloves and olive green jackets and tight pants to draw attention.
Four pairs of perfectly aligned black shoes.
Four stylish hats perfectly placed over the hair tied with blue and white striped hoods.
“Personally, I think they have a normal appearance,” Mr. Tang said, disdainfully.
“The models are beautiful.”
More than one government has tried to clean up the image of China’s urban inspectors.
One city ordered all new recruits to have a degree.
The Guangdong Province changed the greyish green color of the uniforms to a supposedly more attractive blue.
Wuhan, in central China, replaced the use of force with intimidating glances: in 2009, according to a report, 50 officers surrounded a discolic snack cart, and watched it with the frown constantly for half an hour, until the walking salesman picked up his stuff and left.
Xindu, an urban district of 680,000 people in Chengdu, has chosen a radical image change.
Since 2003, the district has added 13 women to its urban police force, specifically chosen for their appearance, proportion and youth.
The idea is to give the rude policeman a softer, feminine side.
Sadly, even Scarlett Johansson would have to struggle to increase China’s petty respect for these city squadrons.
And for good reason, the critics would argue.
Unlike the police, these officers are only authorized to enforce city ordinances, imposing fines and other administrative penalties.
But the Chinese news media routinely portrays a different reality.
In January 2008, Hubei Province inspectors punched a passerby after using his cell phone to film them as they disbanded a protest against a landfill.
Last year, a training manual for Beijing inspectors was stolen and published on the internet, in which it described how to effectively beat criminals without causing them to bleed.
This year, an outgoing Shanghai watermelon salesman suffered brain damage after a reindeer with five officers.
A violent video game, available for download online, features Chinese-trained inspectors attacking street vendors.
"Chengguan has left a scar on the government," China Daily, a national publication, lamented last year after another controversy over tactics.
The newspaper demanded "a really meticulous cleanup."
Skeptics say the current approach is far from this.
After the district requested through a notice eight new female recruits in October, an editorial in The Beijing Evening News questioned whether the women had real duties or were simply a stage distraction.
