Can civilisation be a bridge to unite divisions?
After a remarkable campaign for invective and negativity, this week has sparked a bit of civicism in Washington.
Is it a prelude to a genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a quick turn to the partisan struggle in the capital?
Tuesday’s meeting between President Obama and Congressional leaders did not bring any progress on the major issues to be addressed during the forthcoming session.
But as everyone says, it was at least a courteous discussion of the differences between the two sides, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another empty episode to win party points.
The president’s deficit committee’s public meeting on Wednesday was equally civilized, despite the political differences that remain between members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months generated mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap that still separates members.
That is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
The two sides are now in a trial period, surveying each other to identify signs of co-operativeness and commitment, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and voters’ patience for a renewed party war.
The reason why Tuesday's meeting and subsequent evaluations by the participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and are too deep-rooted to suggest any rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it is taxes, expenses, health care or social assistance, the two parties are at opposite poles.
However, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
“There is no doubt that things have changed with respect to how things are said,” said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
“They are inevitable after the election.
Elections awaken partisan passions, which then become extinct.
That's good."
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda of the outgoing session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of this.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all of the reductions, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a commitment to expand unemployment benefits, probably because Republicans cannot make them believe they are in favor of tax cuts for the rich, denying the unemployment benefit for the unemployed workers.
Following Tuesday’s meeting at the White House, there is greater optimism for a possible deal on these issues during the forthcoming session, along with the ratification of the new Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty (START).
But William Galston, of the Brookings Institution, warns that successful cooperation on pressing issues at the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continued bipartisanship when the new 112th Congress meets in January.
He stated, on the contrary, that it is very likely and even inevitable that a period of disagreement will begin.
“After the things that need to be done are done, in the short term, psychology will turn the situation into a confrontational one,” he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civilisation can lead to true cooperation.
“I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as a rehearsal for the main event of 2012,” he said.
The motives have a lot to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the Tea Party voters, who contributed decisively to its creation.
As much as Republican leaders are aware of the dangers of exaggerating their position, they know they must try to keep their promises to cut state spending and repeal the new health law.
These starting lines are already clearly seen in the initial reactions to the deficit committee's recommendations, which include reform of the tax code and the increase in some taxes and retirement age, and cuts in spending.
Co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken care of one of the hardest jobs in Washington and, in their own assessment, have forcibly put the issue of the deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member committee to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and have been struggling to get close to that figure.
The greatest resistance is among the officials elected to the panel, suggesting that there are, at least currently, few bases or desire for engagement in tax matters.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the Republicans of the White House and those of Congress.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan shocks, when Republicans challenge Obama on the budget, taxes and medical care, followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would cause the change?
The public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a dead end, as happened in 1995, then both parties will watch closely the reaction of the people.
Anyone who thinks they’re losing is likely to change course and seek engagement.
However, this can be an optimistic view.
Partyism and polarization are now larger than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a larger ideological gap between Obama and Republicans in Congress than there was between President Bill Clinton and Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as the mere prelude to a more transcendental election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilization shown this week can be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
A leaked U.S. document portrays Moscow as a paradise of corruption
The control of the city is in the hands of a “cleptocracy,” and leaves a portion of the bribes and protection money it raises directly to the Kremlin, the U.S. Embassy in Russia reported in February.
It was reported that both the police and the Federal Security Service operate huge blackmail systems, which helps explain the high cost of living in Moscow.
They raise money not only from legitimate businesses, but also from organized criminal groups.
Each stratum of bureaucracy, what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called the “vertical authority,” takes its share as money rises on the scale.
The note, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was posted by WikiLeaks on its website on Wednesday.
The note is based on sources whose names have been censored.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still mayor of Moscow, and blames him for much of the corruption.
President Dmitry Medvedev fired him in October, but there has been little evidence of a cleanup since.
Luzhkov and his wife, Yelena Baturina, who owns a major construction company, have consistently denied allegations of corruption over the years, and he has won several libel lawsuits over such allegations.
In September, when asked on a Russian television channel about a documentary that suggested it was corrupt, he stated: "It's madness, a mistress, a nuisance."
According to surveys, Russians overwhelmingly believe that their society is corrupt.
But it is unusual to find the details explained in detail, as they were in the embassy report, and it is unheard of for foreign diplomats to do so.
“The direct links of the Moscow city government to crime have led some to call it ‘dysfunctional’, and to assert that the government functions more as a cleptocracy than as a government,” the statement said.
“Criminal elements enjoy a ‘krysha’ (a term of the criminal world and the mafia that literally means ‘roof’ or protection) crossed by the police, the Federal Security Service (SFS), the Ministry of Internal Affairs (MVD), and the prosecutor’s office, as well as all sectors of the government’s bureaucracy.
“Analysts identify a three-level structure in Moscow’s criminal world.”
"Luzhkov is at the top."
“The SFS, the MVD and the militia are at the second level.”
“Finally, ordinary criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level.”
“This is an ineffective system in which criminal groups fill a vacuum in some areas, because the city does not provide some services.”
The report states that the SFS raises money from larger companies, and that the police are targeting small businesses.
One source, the report said, “explained that Moscow’s commercial owners understand that it is best to get the protection of the MVD and SFS (rather than organized crime groups) because they not only have more weapons, resources and power than criminal groups, but are also protected by law.”
“For this reason, protection against criminal gangs is no longer a priority.”
The note notes that while the fundraising is complete, protection may be irregular; even those who pay are subject to arrest.
Those who don’t pay quickly find their businesses closed for one pretext or another.
Medvedev has spoken several times about fighting corruption, but has confessed that he has made little progress.
The embassy note reports of men taking suitcases, probably full of cash, inside the Kremlin itself.
"In his fight against corruption, Medvedev has to trust the bureaucrats," Georgy Satarov, director of the group of experts at Indem in Moscow, said in a recent interview.
“But he is a part of this bureaucracy.”
“He does not belong to a political class, because there is no longer a political class in Russia.”
Without politics, without an opposition, without a separation of powers, he said, corruption is inevitable.
On a national scale, Indem estimates that corruption costs Russia more than $300 billion a year.
In a recent survey of global perceptions of corruption conducted by the non-governmental organization Transparency International, the country was ranked 154th (countries are ranked from the least to the most corrupt).
The disclosure of the U.S. Embassy note, which didn’t happen until late Moscow time, will surely cause disgust within the Russian government, and although Luzhkov may be blamed for Moscow’s weaknesses, it could be an opportunity for the Kremlin to argue that it is solving the problem.
Interviewed to CNN by Larry King, Putin suggested that WikiLeaks documents could be lies and reacted furiously for a revelation that U.S. diplomats called him Batman and Medvedev Robin.
“The truth of the matter is that this relates to our interaction, which is an important factor in domestic policies in this country,” he said.
"But to be honest with you, let us not suspect that this would have been done with such arrogance, with such pressure and, you know, that it would have been done in such an immoral way."
The veterans of the Red Jemeras forced to face the past
In a sparsely lit concrete classroom, with stained and peeled walls, the director of Anlong Veng High School reminded the man who had built it, the last leader of the Ta Mok Reds.
"Here everyone loves Ta Mok".
“He was a good leader and cared about his people,” said Sreng Kor Ma, 42.
Known as “the butcher” for his brutality during the rule of the Red Jemeras, the commander remains popular in this remote former fortress of the Red Jemeras in northwest Cambodia, where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructures, and where thousands of former soldiers of the organization still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Red Yemenis surrendered to the government, long-held loyalty is finally being challenged in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local forum for truth and reconciliation allowed victims to publicly confront people who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed a high school textbook here that first teaches the history of the Red Jemeras to the children of their former soldiers.
And in July, a United Nations-Cambodia mixed court issued the first sentence of a former member of the Red Yemeni, sentenceing the former head of the well-known Tuol Sleng torture center, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch, to 35 years in prison.
With each of these events, anxiety has grown among the veterans of the Anlong Veng Red Jemeras, complicating efforts for reconciliation and their attempts to re-integrate into Cambodian society.
“There is resentment and fear among the former Red Yemenis, but they can do nothing,” said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodian Documentation Center, an independent organization that investigates the regime.
“For them, life under the Red Jemeras was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil.”
“This is generating divisions within families.”
During the government of Cambodia's Red Jemeras, between 1975 and 1979, about 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, disease or overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrown the Pol Pot-led government in 1979, the remnants of the regime and its military fled to the Cambodian-Thailand border.
There they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last movement that gave up in December 1998.
As Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the guerrilla war from their bases in the mountains and jungles of western Cambodia, Ta Mok cultivated followers in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace deal led to the country’s first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Red Yemeni fighters began deserting towards the government, culminating in the surrenders of Ieng Sary in 1996, and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samp in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had resisted, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the nearby Dangrek Mountains.
He died in a Phnom Penh prison in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Without the support of its benefactors, the oldest Red Yemeni fighters fell into the absolute misery that is common in rural Cambodia, and many feel nostalgic for the movement.
Although a few elite Jemerese officials retained their local administrative posts in exchange for laying down their weapons, the flat soldiers remain poor and unqualified farmers.
“These people have gained little after surrender,” said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which offers public forums across Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
