The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the unwritten, but followed, rules of this sport.
Part of the debate that arose in the reported case is due to the fact that it has been starred by a team of the entity of Real Madrid (who in his anthem presumes of nobility and honor, and who in the past has fined its players for similar acts) and to the technical dramatization orchestrated, apparently by Mourinho and historio.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of behaviour not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, i.e. whether these actions commit fraud; because, in fact, they are actions that respect the sport regulation, but seem to evade their meaning.
The question is to examine the type of damage they cause to the sporting spirit.
One of the goods that the sporting spirit understands is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that was not endangered with these actions, that is, there was no violent play.
Another of these assets that are alluded to by clean play is to prevent the team of the offending players from taking unfair advantage of the opposing team, which did not happen either.
Now, the paradox of the action of Real Madrid players is that it did not fit what we normally characterize as a trap or fraud of law, because its violation of the rules was not made in secret to try to avoid the sanction, but precisely his action tried to be the most obvious in order to receive the punishment of the referee.
They waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage do offenders get in the intentional flaws examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that it is not placed in a disadvantageous situation to the opponent nor profit is obtained in the same game, since obviously the result of the action involves leaving the team itself with fewer players.
And it is also not a useful strategy for the next game, as the club will not be able to count on those players.
The advantage, of course, is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, as the team can be eliminated at the first change, and in addition with this act the players meet a penalty game and pass to the second round of cards, in which the suspension by card accumulation occurs with less than in the first cycle.
So, going through rounds, it’s not so clear that it’s an advantage.
Ultimately, these actions do not go against the sporting spirit, of which it is a part to make strategic decisions that favor making the most of what the rules allow.
In the case that we are concerned, the players did not act to evade the application of the sanction (this would indeed be a clear case of legal fraud), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without bypassing the punishment or running away from it.
Although the boundary between ingenuity and fraud is diffuse, this time I think it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, I think, arises from two factors: because it was two self-ejections and the way in which the transmission of the guideline was carried out to provoke them.
The damage caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not as ethical as it is aesthetic.
