China Holds Targets to Reduce Greenhouse Gases
The country’s representative at COP16 said his country has made enormous efforts to reduce the carbon footprint and detailed that it supports its offer to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by between 40 and 45 percent by 2020.
China maintains its offer to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, said Su Wei, the country’s representative at COP16.
In his first public appearance at the 16th Conference of the Parties to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (COP16), Su Wei said his country has made enormous efforts to reduce the carbon footprint and to reconvert its industry.
In fact, in the last four years, his country has invested $245 million in efforts to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
However, he made it clear that China will not change its objectives, but will continue to work together with the international community on this issue.
He said China’s climate change strategy was divided into four categories: dialogue; capacity building; institution building; and support for pilot programmes.
In all these areas, progress has been made, including the approval last year of a new Energy Act, which collects the targets set for reducing gas emissions, he explained.
On the other hand, he stressed that in China, federal authorities have been working in a coordinated manner with state and local authorities to achieve energy savings, energy efficient use and emission reduction targets.
In addition, several multi-year plans, funded both by the Chinese government and by governments of other countries, are in progress or have already concluded.
For example, he referred to the Energy Efficient Use Program, which was implemented over the past five years and received investments from the United Nations (UN), the government and the private initiative.
A provincial climate change project is also underway, another for changing incandescent spotlights by savers and another for mitigation and adaptation, he detailed.
At the same table, Martin Krol, the government’s scientific adviser on climate change, said China’s efforts have been greater than generally thought.
For example, he explained, the per capita emissions of greenhouse gases in China is six tons per person, while in the United States it is 100 tons; China is responsible for 9 percent of the historical contribution to pollution.
It has also made unprecedented efforts in the use of energy, such as increasing energy efficiency by 20 percent in the last five years and plans to do more by 2020.
