EU changes rules for obtaining visas
Individuals must go to the Visa Applicant Service Centers prior to their interview at the Consular Section; the cost will be lower and also the waiting time.
As of January 10, 2011, the procedure for issuing a visa will change at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates.
With the new procedure, most applicants will have to go to the Visa Applicant Service Centers (ASC) prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
ASC staff will take the biometric information of the applicant, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for applicants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, you will no longer need to make a payment to arrange the appointment, another payment to process the visa application and more for the courier service to deliver the document.
The applicant will only make a one-time payment covering all three services.
The current rate will remain unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa cases on request (including temporary workers visas) and $390 for merchant and investor visas.
People who wish to renew their visa will not have to go to an interview with the Consular Officer, but will only go to the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and take their fingerprints.
Because biometric information will be taken at the ASC, applicants who require a second appointment to be interviewed at the Consular Section will remain in the Consular Section for less time than in the past.
Also, those who apply for visas at the consulates in Ciudad Juarez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of $26.
For more information on the new visa application procedure, visit the following page http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
