The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals an apparent scandal, a scandal that only seems scandalous to the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes on an international scale and foresaw a future dominated by regression.
But let's go step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file created by a secret service (regardless of the nation to which it belongs) is made up exclusively of press cuts.
