This is the mechanism of Dan Brown’s success.
The same goes for secret files.
The informant is lazy, just as he is lazy (or has little anxiety) the head of the secret services (if he could not be, what I know, the editor of the Libération), who only considers what he can recognize certain.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi sent by the U.S. Embassy in Rome to the State Department was the same as published in Newsweek the previous week.
Why, then, have the revelations of these records caused such a tumult?
On the one hand, they say only what every cultivated person already knows, that is, that embassies, at least since World War II and since the Heads of State can call or take the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of some limited representation exercises, have turned into spy centers.
Any viewer who watches research films knows it perfectly, we just don’t seem to know it out of hypocrisy.
In any case, the fact of repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad image of American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can consult the most secret of the most powerful country in the world significantly affects the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal affects both the victims and the "verduggers".
But let us enter into the true nature of what has happened.
In Orwell's time, he could be conceived of as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell’s prophecy has come true since, being able to control every movement thanks to the telephone, every transaction made, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as it is now, that not even the crypts of the secrets of power can escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, elected as the avenger of citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that can no longer keep its own secrets stand?
It is true, as Georg Simmel has already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be disclosed); it is also true that all knowledge of the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret, without secret, it is all power, which they are secret, since they come from the public sphere; but they are secret, as it has done, to reveal them to WikiLeak, as it has done.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but yes, and much more to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound caused to such a powerful power?
It is clear that, in the future, States will no longer be able to put any reserved information on the network, since it would be like publishing it on a streetcartridge.
But it’s also clear that, with current technologies, you can’t expect to hold confidential conversations over the phone.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a Head of State has moved on a plane and contacted one of the counterparts.
How will they be able to maintain private and confidential relationships in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for the time being, my prediction is a science fiction thing and therefore novel, but I imagine governmental agents moving discreetly in diligences with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned from memory or, at least, hiding some written data behind their heels.
That information is then stored, in a single copy, in locked drawers with a key: in the end, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology is currently advancing like a crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet has once again created a telegraph with cables (telephones).
Video tapes (analogous) had allowed film researchers to study a film step by step, moving forward and backward, uncovering all the secrets of editing, while now CDs (digital) only allow moving forward or backward from chapter to chapter, i.e. to enormous proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the departures it entails, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing out of the ordinary that politics and communication techniques take us back to horse cars.
One last comment.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was secretly planned in the embassies.
At present, it is the embassies that ask for confidential information from the press.
Climate: France’s blunders in its funding promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine whether the fast-unlocked funding promises made by developed countries have been fulfilled.
And the French chapuzas have been revealed.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union committed to contribute <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion over three years and France 1.260 million (i.e. <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>420 million per year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has put its best letters on the table to convince its partners that its commitment to fast-start finance is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a major complementary event, the distribution of leaflets...
The Transparency operation was appreciable and appreciated for what it was really worth: developing countries and civil society wanted all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion in 2010, which puts it on track to meeting its <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion commitment in 2012.
But, if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
Under the Copenhagen Agreement, the money must be "new and additional" to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without prejudice to official development aid.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what “new and additional” means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
Nowadays, each one chooses the reference that best suits him.
For example, the European Commission has taken 2009 as a reference: international funding is maintained and 150 million are added over three years in terms of fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers the financing of "all new projects" of 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, it does not refer to the expenditures of previous years or to the total level of official development assistance.
In particular, France's total amount of aid to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), while it seeks to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funds...
Another crucial element is the distribution between donations and loans.
Once again, there are no rules and each chooses the calculation method.
Some, such as France, consider that every euro borrowed equals a donated euro.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often, projects related to the reduction of emissions that are based on more efficient technologies), it is false to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is given... At most, it should be calculated for its commitments only the cost of the loan.
But France does not find this reasoning useful: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros); consult the EU document to see it for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union that makes such frequent use of the loan.
Germany uses it at 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union contributes one euro to fulfill its commitment, France only contributes ten cents and considers the effort comparable.
That's a good trick!
In short, in its fast-start financing, France makes a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to stocks in time and on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
Spending just 36.1 million euros, he gets the impression that he spends 420 million "new and additional", as he had promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has dealt with the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why the other Member States were going to continue to donate when they can just lend?) and in the negotiations, since developing countries are not stupid...
The chapter on early funding is a short-term minuscule in relation to all climate negotiations.
But it could be a grain of sand left over in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope that's not the case.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the rest of the European Union.
But, especially, France could advance the debate on gambling in relation to long-term financing (another essential chapter that is currently being debated): we will not get rid of the issue of the "additional character" or the method of calculating loans.
France could change its stance to become as progressive on this issue as it is on others.
We therefore have the hope of the new Environment Minister, Ms Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France’s quick start and its vision of the “additional character” and the use of loans would help improve the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the negotiations.
Warning about pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals on a day, according to a study published Wednesday by the association Générations Futures (the former movement for the rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which warns that its results “do not have a significant statistical value considering the limited number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem dealt with,” acquired in supermarkets in Oise and Paris between July and September the foods that a child of about ten years old usually consumes on four meals and a snack.
These model meals, which respect the official recommendations (five parts of fresh fruit and vegetables, three of dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day), as well as the treats, were examined in laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other contaminants.
The plate balance is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five are classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances that can act as endocrine disruptors (PE), according to studies by various institutions such as the International Center for Research on Carcinogens.
“Although in virtually all cases, the legal limits for each of the chemicals are not exceeded individually, our study clearly shows that consumers’ exposure to potentially carcinogenic and/or PE contaminants is worrying,” the association notes.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic wastes and three considered safe carcinogens, as well as about twenty wastes that can harm the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, intended as a snack for the school, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to Kenyan greens, included in food, where the study has detected traces of a potent insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, Russian fillet, canned tuna and even bread bar or gum were glued with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, analyses found the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon slice was the most "nutritive" with 34 chemical residues detected and even analysis of the plastic plate used to heat food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The final risk generated by these “contaminant cocktails” for the consumer is “probably underestimated,” the study says.
The Europe Ecology-Les Verts Alliance (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "in the face of the gravity of the situation" to apply a moratorium on the use of pesticides to curb "the increase of diseases associated with civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) indicated the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 in cereals.
